    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-04-24T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-04-24T04:00:00-05:00" n="541"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d541">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">671.116/61: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Rumania</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Owsley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bucharest</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-04-24T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 24, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received April 24—10:50
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. Referring to my telegram No. 6, April 20, 6 a.m., despatched via London.
                    Pending Department’s consideration my written reports may I acknowledge receipt
                    of Rumanian reply; note that suspension order does not prohibit all imports and
                    that goods in customs and in transit will be omitted; say reply has been
                    forwarded with request for further instructions; and request that in the
                    meantime authorities take note of unofficial summary of statement explanatory of
                    most-favored-nation principle broadcast by the Department, April 7th?<note
                        n="13" xml:id="d541fn13">Reference is presumably made to the Department’s
                        press releases of April 1 and 5. For texts, see Department of State, <hi
                            rend="italic">Press Releases</hi>, April 6, 1935, pp. 212 and
                        218.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Owsley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
